Input Planning (Entity Creation & Relationship Setup)
1. Input Planning Is Flexible

How you plan or design input data is completely up to your workflow.
The only important rule:
✔️ Ensure all relationship fields are correctly set in both parent and child entities.


2. Relationship Fields Must Be Filled Properly

Whenever an entity has a relationship (One‑to‑One, One‑to‑Many, Many‑to‑Many, etc.):

You must assign the correct relationship object.
Example: If Employee has a Department field, that field must be assigned before saving.




3. Two Ways to Build Parent–Child Objects
Method 1: Create Parent First, Then Add Child

Step 1: Create and save the parent entity.
Step 2: Create the child entity and link it to the parent.
Step 3: Save the child (or parent again depending on cascade rules).

✔ Useful when child depends on a parent primary key.

Method 2: Initialize Parent Along With Child

Create a parent object and directly set its child object(s).
Example:

Create Department
Then create Employee list and assign it inside Department before saving.



✔ Useful for cascaded relationships where parent automatically persists children.